  <item>
    <title>Overview of a High-Performance Drupal Architecture</title>
    <link>http://drupalcampcharlotte.com/sessions/overview-high-performance-drupal-architecture</link>
    <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-type-userreference field-field-speakers&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;field-label&quot;&gt;Speaker(s):&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;
                    &lt;a href=&quot;http://drupalcampcharlotte.com/users/rgristroph&quot; title=&quot;View user profile.&quot;&gt;Robert Ristroph&lt;/a&gt;        &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This talk will describe a linux-based stack designed to serve up a Drupal application in a high-performance way. It will cover reverse proxy caches (Varnish), Apache vs. nginx, the APC opcode cache, memcache and redis, expanding the stack&lt;br /&gt;
accross clusters, and MySQL database replication.  The &quot;mercury stack&quot; will be covered, along with tweaks and changes that have become standard since it was first described.  Series of block diagrams of a single server, small cluster, and large cluster will be shown and explained.  At the end we will discuss some of the hard scaling problems that don&#039;t have standard solutions yet - clustered file storage, large database write loads, etc.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;fieldset class=&quot;fieldgroup group-audience&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-type-text field-field-experience&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;field-label&quot;&gt;Experience level:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;
                    Advanced        &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/fieldset&gt;
</description>
     <comments>http://drupalcampcharlotte.com/sessions/overview-high-performance-drupal-architecture#comments</comments>
